# ADR-0018 — Intent-Centric Architecture

- Status: Accepted
- Date: 2026-07-19
- Deciders: Pharos Architecture Team

---

# Context

Many AI frameworks are built around conversations, prompts or messages.

Their execution pipelines typically begin with conversational artifacts such
as:

- chat history
- user messages
- prompts
- conversation state

This tightly couples the execution engine to a conversational interface.

Pharos AI Operating System is intended to support far more than chat.

Examples include:

- APIs
- background jobs
- scheduled workflows
- autonomous agents
- mobile applications
- IDE integrations
- command line interfaces
- event-driven systems

A conversation should therefore be considered one possible input—not the
foundation of the architecture.

---

# Decision

Intent is the universal execution primitive of the platform.

Every execution request must ultimately be represented as a RuntimeIntent.

Conversation is one possible producer of RuntimeIntent.

It is not the execution model.

```
Conversation
        │
        ▼

 API Request
        │
        ▼

 Scheduled Task
        │
        ▼

 Autonomous Agent
        │
        ▼

 Event Trigger
        │
        ▼

 RuntimeIntent
        │
        ▼

 Runtime
```

The Runtime never executes conversations.

It executes intents.

---

# RuntimeIntent

RuntimeIntent represents executable intent.

It contains only the information required for execution.

Examples include:

- objective
- constraints
- metadata
- execution preferences

RuntimeIntent never contains UI concepts.

Examples of UI concepts:

- chat messages
- prompt formatting
- markdown rendering
- conversation history

These belong to higher layers.

---

# Producers

RuntimeIntent may be created by many different producers.

Examples:

- Chat Agent
- REST API
- CLI
- Scheduler
- Event Bus
- Another Agent
- Workflow
- External Automation

The Runtime treats every producer identically.

---

# Runtime Responsibilities

The Runtime accepts RuntimeIntent.

It does not know:

- where the intent originated
- who created it
- whether it came from a human
- whether it came from another AI

Execution remains origin-independent.

---

# Conversation Layer

Conversation is an application concern.

Conversation systems are responsible for:

- parsing messages
- maintaining chat history
- user interaction
- formatting responses

Conversation systems eventually produce RuntimeIntent.

---

# Agent Responsibilities

Agents transform information into intent.

Agents may use:

- Memory
- Knowledge
- Tools
- Reasoning

The output of reasoning is RuntimeIntent.

---

# Architectural Principles

## Intent Is Universal

Everything executable becomes RuntimeIntent.

No exceptions.

---

## Conversation Independence

Removing chat support must not require changes to Runtime.

Adding voice support must not require changes to Runtime.

Adding scheduled execution must not require changes to Runtime.

---

## Transport Independence

RuntimeIntent is independent from transport protocols.

Possible transports include:

- HTTP
- WebSocket
- CLI
- gRPC
- Message Queue
- Local API

Runtime remains unchanged.

---

## Human and AI Equality

The Runtime makes no distinction between:

- human-generated intent
- AI-generated intent
- scheduled intent
- event-generated intent

All are executed identically.

---

# Dependency Rules

Runtime depends only on RuntimeIntent.

Conversation depends on Runtime.

Runtime never depends on conversation.

Agents never expose conversation objects to Runtime.

---

# Alternatives Considered

## Conversation-Centric Runtime

Rejected.

This prevents Runtime reuse outside chat applications.

---

## Prompt-Centric Runtime

Rejected.

Prompts are implementation details of LLMs.

They are not execution primitives.

---

## API-Specific Runtime

Rejected.

Execution should remain transport-independent.

---

# Consequences

Positive:

- reusable Runtime
- transport independence
- chat independence
- API-first architecture
- automation-friendly
- event-driven support
- future-proof execution model

Negative:

- requires an explicit translation layer
- application developers must generate RuntimeIntent

The architectural benefits significantly outweigh the additional layer.

---

# Future Evolution

Future producers may include:

- robotic systems
- IoT devices
- autonomous companies
- operating systems
- distributed AI networks

All ultimately produce RuntimeIntent.

The Runtime Core remains unchanged.

